title: Grateful Dead Live at Zoo Amphitheater on 1981-07-05
lineage: Nak CM700's> Sony D-5> MC> DAT> CD
description: Shakedown Street-> Promised Land, Candyman-> Cassidy, Brown Eyed Women-> CC Rider, They Love Each Other, Mama Tried-> Mexicali Blues, Althea-> Let It Grow Samson & Delilah, Don't Ease Me In-> The Music Never Stopped, Ship of Fools-> Lost Sailor-> Saint Of Circumstance-> He's Gone-> Drums-> The Other One-> Stella Blue-> Around & Around-> Johnny B. Goode, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text: Recording just OK The pitch needs to be significantly lowered

This Show Rocks! Out of all of the shows I saw through the Mid-West.  This one was the best.  Jerry hit the ground running and never stopped.  Not a bad version of any tune here.  You have GOT to GET this one!

Rockin' show in OKC The boys at my homestate, and they didnt dissapoint. The recording is decent, the show kicks ass. Check it out, this show is very under-rated.
Watch out for the cut in He's Gone.

Underrated Show This show does not get enough love IMHO. The Zoo Amph was a real nice setting for a Dead show, a smallish (6-7,000 Capacity) surrounded by large trees with re clay underfoot.

The show kicks off with one of the great Shakedowns ever, Jerry rips off some very nice and unique licks during the meat of the jam. The whole first set is very well played with superb versions of the afore mentioned Shakedown, Candyman, Cassidy, CC Rider, Althea and Let It Grow.

Set 2 is real sweet, 7 pre-drum songs, including Don't Ease > Music Never Stopped, both rarities for the second set. The LS>St> He's Gone is very sweet and the after drums features a flawless Other One> Stella jam.

All in All a nice show that a lot of people do not seem to have.

Get It This recording actually has spectacular sound quality for an aud. Has all lows, highs, and vocals represented well. I found though that it does take a little tweaking with an eq to drop down the pitch a bit. Oh yeah, and they play pretty darn good too.
sound quality is Awesome nice , smoothe, hot shakedown. shades of Gainsville FLA-1980...like the pace
Zoo Can't Be Serious !! Purple Gel's review below is on point:  This show should get much more love.  Another great one from '81
Pitch The pitch needs to be lowered by 1%

Brown-eyed Madness!!! The brown-eyed Woman on this show is probably the best one I've heard.  Barring any quality of show recording this is complete 'FIRE' 4 complete measures of Jerry soloing.  Dont think thats ever happened before or after. Hot Hot Stuff!!!
- Another good show, pitch notwithstanding, and a very nice recording.
Stellar Let It Grow Jerry is totally in the zone.

a tasty treat from the early eighties  Yes, this show is well-worth archiving for future listening and sharing.  Jerry smokes it on quite a few highlights, Bobby has hits his stride on a kick ass CC Rider early in and the rhythm is there throughout both sets keeping it all churning forward!
